Area Reviews - An Introduction                                     Rev. 1.3
===============================

The area review process is aimed at ensuring that new and refurbished areas
meet a minimum standard before becoming active. All areas, regardless of
how generally competent the coder is, should be submitted for review.

In software terms, an area review is analogous to an acceptance test. It is
not a substitute for internal testing and debugging. For the reviewer, an
area review should be a relatively painless process of verifying that the
area submitted meets certain criteria characteristic of a "good" area. Too
often submitted areas have too many defects, leading to long, drawn out
reviews and general dissatisfaction among all parties.

Submitting an area for review (for the area coder)
--------------------------------------------------

When you have completed your area to the point where it is ready to be
reviewed, you need to use the sumbit area command. 
THIS CAN ONLY BE DONE ON THE DEVELOPMENT VERSION OF THE GAME.

You will be asked to provide the directory path for the area where your
header file should be located. i.e. /players/violator/asgard/

You will then be asked to provide the start room for your area. 
This is the room which is to be connected to the game. 

The next part required is a simple description, which should be just
a title. i.e Hyperborea Arctic Elf Camp. Do not make this title long
winded. 

Lastly you will be required to type a description of the area, in this
description we require the filenames of all uniques and any other
features you may feel could be of concern. Ensure you give a decent
description so that your reviewers know what to expect.

These will be assigned to an appropriate reviewer. It doesn't hurt to tell
higher-ups that you've done this, especially if the issues are not being
assigned very fast.

Conducting a review (for the area reviewer)
-------------------------------------------

Reviewers will be asigned one of the three aspects of the review process.

To ensure the integrity of the process a Mentor can not conduct a review
on their Mentees. 

The process is then to go through the area to verify that the code/content/balance 
meets the criteria for an acceptable area. Some reviewers may find the area 
checklists (wizhelp sections 8.5 to 8.7 of this document) to be useful when       |
reviewing an area. Any defects or deficiencies should be recorded and the 
coder notified of these problems through the review command (see wizhelp 8.8). 

When the area has no remaining problems to be resolved, he/she can close 
that portion of the review, as completed (see wizhelp 8.8). Note that in some
cases, there may need to be multiple review/repair cycles before an area
is acceptable. 

Sometimes a reviewer will find that an area is so badly done that it is far 
too much work to point out all the problems. In these cases the area 
should be sent back to the coder for overall improvement and
resubmission, instead of wasting the reviewer's time.

